<section xmlns="http://xml.house.gov/schemas/uslm/1.0" style="-uslm-lc:I80" id="idb99d45ca-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8" identifier="/us/usc/t18/s3482"><num value="3482">§ 3482.</num><heading> Evidence and witnesses—(Rule)</heading><note id="idb99d45cb-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8">
<heading style="-uslm-lc:I71" class="centered"><inline class="small-caps">See Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure</inline></heading>
<p style="-uslm-lc:I21" class="indent0 fontsize7">Competency and privileges of witnesses and admissibility of evidence governed by principles of common law, Rule 26.</p>
</note>
<sourceCredit id="idb99d45cc-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8">(<ref href="/us/act/1948-06-25/ch645">June 25, 1948, ch. 645</ref>, <ref href="/us/stat/62/833">62 Stat. 833</ref>.)</sourceCredit>
<notes type="uscNote" id="idb99d45cd-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8">
<note style="-uslm-lc:I74" role="crossHeading" topic="editorialNotes" id="idb99d45ce-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8"><heading class="centered"><b>Editorial Notes</b></heading></note>
<note style="-uslm-lc:I75" topic="referencesInText" id="idb99d45cf-47c4-11f1-9a61-b1559996dfe8">
<heading class="centered smallCaps">References in Text</heading><p style="-uslm-lc:I21" class="indent0">Rule 26 of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, referred to in text, was amended in 1972. The subject matter is covered by the Federal Rules of Evidence, set out in the Appendix to Title 28, Judiciary and Judicial Procedure.</p>
</note>
